A New $META for DAOs

Sunny Shi

Sep 3, 2024 ⋅  19 min read

Key Insights

  • Crypto governance frameworks within DAOs and Foundations are flawed, marked by several critical shortcomings.
  • Onchain Futarchy presents a viable solution to these governance limitations, gaining traction as crypto prediction markets rise in prominence.
  • MetaDAO is leading the charge in this area, pioneering a working Futarchy protocol and positioning itself as the first DAO to be entirely governed by the market.
  • MetaDAO’s spot token, META, benefits from the platform’s adoption, as the DAO strives to become a revenue-generating protocol that connects DAOs and traders through its innovative decision market platform.

Introduction

Crypto governance is broken. Despite the laundry list of onchain governance-related issues, there have been limited attempts to develop comprehensive solutions. An ambitious proposition that has emerged is Futarchy, a governance model that applies prediction market infrastructure to decentralized decision-making. MetaDAO, a related project built around its native token, aims to not only validate the effectiveness of Futarchy but also extend its application across every DAO in crypto, and potentially beyond.

This report seeks to analyze the limitations of existing crypto governance, explore how Futarchy can address the key concerns, and highlight how MetaDAO is pioneering this approach. At the end, we share our views on the revenue opportunities for the project.

Crypto’s Flawed Governance

In traditional systems, countries are led by politicians, and Fortune 500 companies are managed by executives. In the realm of crypto, the role of governance falls to Decentralized Autonomous Organizations (DAOs) and Foundations.

The governance mechanisms in crypto are flawed. DAOs and Foundations face numerous bottlenecks and have yet to develop innovative responses to these issues. Below, we outline some of the most pressing limitations:

  • Centralized Voting Power: The concentration of voting power within crypto organizations has become a focal point of concern, with some of the most prominent and influential entities in the space exhibiting alarmingly centralized voting dynamics. The delegate system, which allows token holders to assign their voting power to a chosen representative, exacerbates these issues and often results in disproportionate influence being held by a few delegates.
  • Low Voter Participation: The dynamics described above have also contributed to notably low voter participation, even in the most critical of decisions. For example, MakerDAO's pivotal Endgame proposal saw only 15% participation relative to its circulating market cap. In contrast, the 2020 U.S. election achieved a 67% voter turnout, while corporate proxy votes typically see an average shareholder participation rate of 80%.
  • Numerous Attack Vectors: Due in part to low voter participation, DAOs are inherently vulnerable to coordinated governance attacks. A notable example occurred with Compound this July, where an attacker secured a large number of delegated votes just before their own proposal closed, successfully swinging the vote in their favor. After multiple failed attempts at controlling the vote, the final move required just an additional 228,000 COMP token (priced at $12 million) delegated from 5 wallets to turn the tides in the attacker’s favor. COMP was trading at a circulating market cap of over $400 million, 37x the market value of the swing votes.
  • Conflicts of Interest: Conflicts of interest pose another key concern for teams. While these conflicts may not always result from malicious intent, undisclosed relationships can severely damage the credibility and reputation of these organizations when they are uncovered. Major DAOs like Optimism and Maker have struggled with the public outcry from perceived conflicts of interests. In addition, it is also difficult for teams and delegates to avoid this outcome, as many have broad networks throughout crypto.
  • Slow and Laborious Processes: DAOs and Foundations are notoriously slow-moving, with proposal processes that are both lengthy and complicated. For instance, Ethereum Improvement Proposals (EIPs) require navigating a series of complex steps across multiple forums, from Discord discussions to GitHub repositories. This intricate and time-consuming process has resulted in only 61 core EIPs being passed over the last eight years.

These challenges have eroded confidence in the efficacy of existing crypto governance models. In response, a growing community has turned to the concept of Futarchy as a potential solution.

Introducing Futarchy and MetaDAO

Futarchy, according to leading proponent Robin Hanson, is a societal governance system that derives policy from market insights instead of from elected officials. It was originally meant to represent an alternative for democracy. Hanson proposed that Futarchy could be implemented by first measuring national welfare, and then leveraging betting markets to speculate on whether policy decisions would improve those metrics. He argued that with Futarchy, countries could make more wealth-generative decisions as markets are better than individuals at aggregating information and remaining unbiased.

While Hanson's proposal was largely theoretical, the recent rise of prediction markets in crypto — exemplified by platforms like Polymarket — has provided a practical framework for Futarchy. These markets have demonstrated their potential to generate insightful predictions by harvesting the speculation of traders through crypto rails.

MetaDAO - The Futarchy Service Provider

Enter MetaDAO. Rather than attempting to overhaul governments, MetaDAO seeks to apply the principles of Futarchy within the context of fixing DAOs. MetaDAO proposes a future where DAOs can make more objective, decentralized, and informed decisions by using their Futarchy protocol, directly addressing crypto’s governance limitations. The project went live in November of 2023 with the simple goal of bringing Futarchy to other DAOs as a viable product.

Currently, DAO’s have no simple mechanism to employ Futarchy within their own governance practices. Futarchy is difficult to understand and daunting to facilitate. As governance is a mission critical function, most DAOs are probably unwilling to take on the responsibility of creating and managing a decision market from scratch even if they want to experiment with the concept.

MetaDAO aims to become the leading B2B Futarchy service provider, offering DAOs a platform to conduct their proposals while also serving as a hub for traders speculating on those proposals. Although MetaDAO's decision market product is functional, it is still in the early stages of development. Despite this, Solana DAOs like Drift, Deans List, and FutureDAO have already signed on and conducted proposals. MetaDAO also fully governs itself through its Futarchy protocol using its native token, META on Solana, positioning itself as the first subject of its experimental approach. The DAO will continue refining its protocol and advising clients based on its own experiences and outcomes.

How MetaDAO’s Product Works

MetaDAO's decision market platform allows traders to risk real capital to speculate on whether a proposal will be bullish or bearish for the DAO's spot token. A decision market is a conditional voting market used to pass or fail proposals. Decision markets rely on conditional tokens, which enables if-then trading logic based on binary outcomes. The same technology is also used in prediction markets, as detailed in our previous report on Polymarket.

MetaDAO leverages conditional tokens to create two temporary markets during a vote: one contingent on the proposal passing and the other on it failing. Traders can participate in these markets individually, expressing their views on the spot token's price based on the anticipated outcome. Conditional tokens are necessary because they allow for the reversal of trades when specific conditions aren't met—something that chains like Solana currently do not support.

Tokens included in a MetaDAO voting process include:

  • pMETA - conditional META tokens used to trade in the pass market
  • fMETA - conditional META tokens used to trade in the fail market
  • pUSDC - conditional USDC tokens used to trade in the pass market
  • fUSDC - conditional USDC tokens used to trade in the fail market

When engaging with a MetaDAO decision market, tokens in the pass market (pMETA/pUSDC) convert to spot tokens only if the proposal passes, while tokens in the fail market (fMETA/fUSDC) convert to spot tokens only if the proposal fails.

For example, depositing one META mints one pMETA and one fMETA. Holding both without trading ensures that, at the end of the session, the holder receives one spot META back depending on the proposal's outcome. This system maintains one fully collateralized spot META, even with two conditional tokens generated, as only one market will ultimately convert back to spot.

To enable trading, the organizer seeds liquidity in AMMs for both the pass and fail market. Let's explore a few examples of the different groups of market participants in a MetaDAO decision market and the options available to them.

Example Trading Scenarios

META holders can sell or accumulate META contingent on their preferred outcome

  • Here we evaluate two market participants, Alice and Bob, each with opposing views on the same proposal. Alice is bearish on the proposal and seeks to reduce her META exposure if it passes, while Bob is bullish and aims to accumulate more META if it succeeds.
  • Alice deposits META to mint corresponding pMETA and fMETA, then sells pMETA into the pass market AMM, intending to reduce her position if the proposal passes but maintain it if it fails.
  • Conversely, Bob deposits USDC to mint corresponding pUSDC and fUSDC, using pUSDC to buy pMETA in the AMM. Bob accumulates more tokens if the proposal passes and refrains if it fails.

Short-term trader exploiting price discrepancies

  • In this scenario, Charles, a short-term trader without a long-term outlook on META, spots an opportunity when fMETA's price drops significantly during the trading session, believing it to be undervalued.
  • To take advantage, Charles deposits USDC to mint pUSDC and fUSDC, then purchases fMETA in the fail market, anticipating a price correction during the trading session.
  • When he is correct and the price rebounds, he sells his fMETA at a higher value, securing a profit if the proposal fails. If the proposal passes, Charles remains net neutral.

Noise trader focused on pushing a proposal through

  • Disruptive Danny is determined to push a proposal through and is willing to spend significantly to achieve that goal, acting as a noise trader.
  • Danny deposits both META and USDC into the conditional vault, then indiscriminately buys pMETA in the pass market to raise prices and sells fMETA in the fail market to lower prices, aiming to increase the proposal's chances of passing.
  • Danny transacts at unattractive prices from a profit perspective but he remains focused on getting the proposal passed, even at a potential loss.

In a perfectly efficient decision market, the spot token would price in the changing values of both the pass market and the fail market, as well as the probabilities of a pass or fail.

At the end of the trading session, the proposal passes if the time-weighted-average-price (TWAP) of pMETA is higher than that of fMETA, and vice versa.

Example Proposals

An example of a successful proposal is the approval of MetaDAO's Q3 roadmap, which was largely met with favorable opinions. Throughout the trading session, traders attributed a slight premium to META’s value if the proposal passed, while the fail market tokens traded at a discount to spot prices. As the likelihood of the proposal passing rose, the prices in the spot and pass markets began to converge. Ultimately, the TWAP difference between the pass and fail markets was substantial enough to meet the threshold for passing the proposal.

An example of an unsuccessful proposal was Drift’s attempt to fund a new Artemis Labs data and analytics dashboard, raised by an Artemis Labs representative. Although closely contested, the fail market traded higher than the pass market for most of the voting period, leading to a higher fail TWAP price. Drift’s spot token declines appeared to influence the price action in both markets, with prices converging near spot value by session close. Ultimately, the proposal failed, likely because the market viewed funding the project as an unattractive use of Drift’s funds.

For partners like Drift, MetaDAO allows each participating DAO to set the terms of their proposal rubric, including the length of the trading session and the TWAP spread required for a proposal to pass.

Do Traders Incur Risk?

A common question about MetaDAO’s decision markets is whether traders are truly putting their capital at risk. In all the scenarios mentioned, traders do incur risk.

Just like trading any spot token, buying conditional tokens at overvalued prices means you’ve overpaid and selling conditional tokens at undervalued prices means you’ve left profit on the table. The one caveat for decision market traders is that your P&L only materializes if the market you are trading in settles to spot. If a proposal passes, only your P&L from the pass market carries forward, and the reverse applies if the proposal fails. In either scenario, any losses in a settled market are as real as those in spot trading.

As thus, traders are incentivized to trade prudently and inform themselves on the implications of a proposal. Let’s take a look at how MetaDAO’s decision markets address crypto’s governance limitations.

MetaDAO vs. Governance Limitations

Here’s how MetaDAO plans to help DAOs eliminate the aforementioned limitations.

  • Voting Concentration - By opening decision-making to the broader market, any number of traders can dictate the outcome of key proposals, as opposed to a few influential delegates. Decisions are decided by trading flows, not the distribution of supply, ensuring that no single actor can maintain over 50% voting control indefinitely.
  • Voter Participation - Unlike traditional voting mechanisms, MetaDAO incentivizes participation by aligning it with profit. Traders are motivated to engage when there's financial gain, irrespective of a proposal's likelihood of passing or failing. This approach expands the pool of participants beyond just current META holders, giving a voice to a larger and more diverse group of decision makers.
  • Attack Vectors - MetaDAO reduces the risk of governance attacks by using time-weighted average prices (TWAPs) and incentivizing countertraders to neutralize market manipulation from noise traders for profit. By determining votes based on average prices over the course of a trading session, MetaDAO prevents last-minute vote swings and ensures a more stable decision-making process.
  • Conflict of Interest - Delegates can outsource decision-making to the market, which serves as an unbiased arbiter, eliminating the risk of backdoor deals or undisclosed relationships influencing votes. MetaDAO’s reliance on a third party for governance mirrors the blame-as-a-service model sometimes seen in management consulting, where the consequences of key decisions fall under the responsibility of a consultant, allowing internal actors to maintain their goodwill.
  • Slow and Laborious - Because traders are quicker to aggregate relevant information, proposals can resolve quicker and more efficiently. Assuming the proposer provides the necessary contextual information for speculators to inform their trades, participants are incentivized to come to their own conclusion quickly and in real-time.

Promising Signs from MetaDAO’s Own Proposals

MetaDAO’s own governance is acting as a proof of concept for onchain Futarchy. Despite the youth of the project, three critical votes have already demonstrated its efficacy:

  • Proposal 6 saw Ben Hawkins, Solana’s head of staking, attempt to manipulate a vote to test the Futarchy model. Ben crafted a proposal for the DAO treasury to allocate him approximately 10% of the token supply at a 38% discount to spot prices. He then contributed $250,000 to manipulate the vote in his favor by buying conditional META tokens in the "pass" markets and selling them in the "fail" markets. However, as Ben had acted as a typical noise trader, profit-seeking participants quickly counter traded his activity by selling into his high bids and buying into his low sells. Ultimately, Ben's efforts were unsuccessful in swaying the price action in his favor, and the proposal failed. The outcome demonstrates the robustness of MetaDAO’s mechanisms against attackers.
  • Proposal 7 involved Pantera Capital’s attempt to invest in META through a proposal similar to a previous one, but without offering a discount. However, as META's price surged during the proposal's voting period, many DAO members viewed the proposal as effectively providing Pantera with a free, in-the-money call option. Consequently, the proposal failed. The results underscore how Futarchy allows the market, rather than any internal individual or entity, to decide proposals, freeing MetaDAO’s team from the pressure of rejecting a prominent investor.
  • MetaDAO’s most recent proposal sparked intense debate over a controversial plan to introduce a Pump.Fun fork. A bullish anonymous holder, unknown to the community, injected over $50,000 into the effort to push the proposal through. This activity generated over $500,000 in trading volume across just 43 participants, with each trader executing more than 30 trades on average in an effort to either bring the proposal down or profit off of the associated noise. The proposal, which was ultimately defeated by a narrow margin, highlights how even relatively obscure individuals can make their presence felt in votes, and how the gravity and excitement surrounding a proposal can drive high levels of voter participation.

While these voting sessions have had relatively low mindshare across crypto, early signs from key MetaDAO proposals are encouraging for the soundness of Futarchy as a DAO governance mechanism.

MetaDAO’s Business Model

For META holders, the primary goal is for the DAO to generate revenue. The DAO passed a proposal to offer Futarchy-as-a-Service (FaaS) to interested DAOs, enabling them to experiment with decision markets through MetaDAO’s interface. Although MetaDAO's product is functional, it is still in the early stages of development. External DAOs that have conducted proposals currently do not compensate MetaDAO for its services. Evaluating MetaDAO’s potential involves considering how they can monetize the product going forward.

Futarchy-as-a-Service

MetaDAO delivers value by offering a liquid, configurable, plug-and-play platform that partners can use to facilitate their own DAO votes. On the demand side, MetaDAO aims to attract attention and traders to each proposal, similar to how DEXs and market makers assist protocols in bootstrapping liquidity.

As MetaDAO demonstrates its value proposition, it can monetize through several business lines.

  • Charging DAOs for use of the Futarchy protocol. The platform's code is BSL-licensed, allowing the DAO to charge client DAOs a monthly fee for access to both the code and the site. While DAOs and protocols can technically write their own code, clients gain significant advantages by staying on the original platform, including continuous improvements from MetaDAO and the benefit of an aggregated pool of traders and speculative capital, which enhances the overall effectiveness and liquidity of the decision markets. Some comparisons here include Realms and Squads which both provide Solana DAO tooling and servicing.
  • Collecting trader fees in conditional markets. Since MetaDAO is essentially acting as an exchange to facilitate trader activity for proposal speculation, the platform can take maker/taker fees on their active markets.
  • Providing ad-hoc Futarchy consulting services. As Futarchy may be confusing for most DAOs, MetaDAO slots in as a decision market expert who can guide clients through the process. The DAO may also be able to work on ad-hoc proposals in the future, which require specific functionality. A comparison for this vertical can be drawn to Gauntlet, a DAO strategy consultancy who leverages both human resources and quantitative dashboards to help DAOs like Uniswap, Aave, Maker and Compound make informed decisions.

To make this happen, MetaDAO is putting in the early legwork. The team is building a Futarchy product specifically for facilitating grants, hiring a full fledged team, and becoming a U.S. corporate entity.

$META’s Potential - Generating Revenue

The DAO’s spot token META should benefit directly from ongoing progress in the FaaS product, as the protocol develops into a cash generative business.

We model out META’s potential revenue build. Our main assumptions include:

  • DAO client growth: We must first estimate how many DAOs could onboard MetaDAO’s Futarchy protocol. Realms’ website mentions that there are 800+ Solana DAOs using their free product. Only about ~300 seem to be charted DAOs. For MetaDAO, the amount of DAOs that would be willing to experiment with Futarchy, as well as pay for it, would represent a much smaller sample than that. We estimate early conversion ratios over the next year to be 5-10%, which represents roughly 15-30 DAOs. Growth from there would factor in continued conversion and growth in new DAOs on Solana.
  • Monthly licensing fee: Squads Pro, which provides Solana multisig capabilities, charges ~$399 a month for its services. We use this as an anchor point for MetaDAO fee assumptions, assuming a realistic fee rate to be between $250 to $500 a month.
  • Platform Volumes: To start, MetaDAO’s most recent proposal generated roughly ~$510,000 in volume. As trades in the non-finalized market are reverted, we cut this volume in half for potential fee capture. With this in mind, we estimate that proposals can do between $100,000 to $300,000 in monetizable volume, which will grow as more traders figure out how to trade decision markets. External DAOs on MetaDAO’s platform tend to do between 1-3 proposals a month, which we add as a multiplier to figure out monthly volume.
  • Exchange fees: Average DEX taker fees are around ~0.2%. We assume an average take rate of 15 to 25 basis points.
  • Consulting fees: As consulting is ad hoc, this is the hardest business line to estimate. We leave it out of the model and think of it as upside to projected revenue.

We believe MetaDAO stands to generate outsized revenue from trading fees as the volume per proposal increases alongside the number of DAOs using the platform. As more traders engage in decision markets, the operating leverage in trading revenues is likely to grow. If MetaDAO can onboard 50 DAOs by 2027, with each submitting two proposals per month, we project the platform could handle over $30 million in monthly trading volumes.

As such, MetaDAO could become the “Polymarket” for decision markets, turning speculation into actionable change for interested DAOs, while monetizing both the insights and the trading activity. In crypto, where genuine revenue from value-added services is scarce, MetaDAO has the potential to become one of the few projects that truly delivers on this promise.

It is important to keep in mind that the project is still in its infancy, with a relatively small number of contributors actively engaging in discussions within the Discord channel to shape the DAO's future. While the team must effectively execute the roadmap, all key decisions are, in alignment with the project's vision, made through Futarchy.

Notable Risks

DAO Activity on Solana is Limited

As a Solana project, MetaDAO’s initial client base is limited to Solana-based DAOs. Compared to Ethereum and L2 ecosystems, there are fewer large-scale DAOs on Solana.

Barriers to Entry are Low

MetaDAO’s technological moat isn’t pronounced, as conditional tokens are not novel and can easily be forked. In its early stages, MetaDAO is prone to being copycatted on other chains and by incumbent prediction markets like Polymarket.

It may also be possible that protocols try to implement Futarchy in-house, in an effort to avoid any reliance on a third party.

Inertia Prevents Adoption

Futarchy is radical, and until it reaches public acceptance, may be too esoteric of a solution. Furthermore, current DAO delegates are unlikely to want to relinquish voting control to an open market, decreasing FaaS’ chances of adoption.

We think the low-hanging fruit for MetaDAO’s initial business development efforts is for newly formed DAOs, of which there are plenty on Solana.

Conclusion

DAOs in their current form are flawed, struggling with centralized voting, low participation, and repeated governance attacks. Crypto-enabled Futarchy offers a promising solution by aligning decision-making with market incentives, leading to more informed and robust voting mechanisms. MetaDAO is pioneering this onchain approach guided by a bold and ambitious vision to reshape how DAOs operate and usher in a new era of decentralized governance. With Futarchy-as-a-Service under development, META is in the early innings of becoming a profit-seeking business.
